{"id":"astro-ph/0603140","submitter":"John Hodge","authors":"John C. Hodge","title":"Scalar potential model of the CMB radiation temperature","comments":"4 pages, submitted to Phys. Rev. D-15","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  A derivation of a theoretical, time average, cosmic microwave background\n(CMB), Planckian temperature V of the universe remains a challenge. A scalar\npotential model (SPM) that resulted from considerations of galaxy cells is\napplied to deriving a value for V. The heat equation is solved for a cell with\nthe boundary conditions of SPM Source and Sink characteristics, with simplified\ncell characteristics, and with zero initial temperature. The universe is a\ncollection of cells. The CMB radiation is black body radiation with the cells\nacting as radiators and absorbers. Conventional thermodynamics is applied to\ncalculate V = 2.718 K. The temperature and matter content of cells are finely\ncontrolled by a feedback mechanism. Because time is required for matter to flow\nfrom Sources to Sinks, the radiation temperature of cells cycles about V after\nan initial growth phase. If the universe is like an ideal gas in free expansion\nand is not in thermal equilibrium, then the pressure and volume follow the\nmeasured CMB temperature vm = 2.725 K. Therefore, increasing vm >V equates to\nan expansion pressure on matter and expanding volume.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 6 Mar 2006 19:49:28 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
